  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - SHADOWKNIGHT</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>DUELING STRATEGIES CLASS BY CLASS</font> - <small>Zekris Shadowblaze, Fennin Ro</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>As a level 25 DE SK, I have dueled quite a few times, both recreationally and when honor is at stake. As an SK, you have several advantages over other classes in PvP, first and foremost: your melee ability, the "Darkness" line of spells, Fear, and your pet (close quarters helps as well).<P><P>Now, rather than just listing general strategies, I will offer some basic strategies based on the general class of the person you are dueling.<P>Casters w/pets: Generally, right off the bat the caster will send their pet in to tank and begin to cast spells. Of course, you are at your most effective in melee with the caster, so you need to get rid of the pet somehow. One method (excellent if the caster is a kiter) is to darkness the pet and start chasing the caster, thus leaving the caster unable to cast his spells and leaving his pet limping along far behind. In turn, if the caster pauses to asses the situation, either run up and whack away (remember, it is best to save HT for when it will serve as a death blow, dropping them from mid-low health to nothing at all) or darkness/fear them. Of course, if you have a pet summoned as well, put them on the caster to tank (bash especially), which makes this scenario much easier. Now, another option, often best used when you don't have a pet nor do you have sufficient time to get off a darkness before the pet hits you, is to shadow step, hopefully putting you out of range of the caster's spells and sending the pet charging off after you. Then you can darkness/fear the pet and the caster is all yours. When meleeing the casters, your best bet is to use your most high dmg weapon (2hs) rather than attempting to stun them with your bash (if you are a Troll/Ogre, then you have the best of both worlds). Nothing scares a caster more than being hit for high dmg and not having their pet to save them.<P><P>Wizards: Wizard duels can either be extremely easy or irritatingly difficult. Most wizards will go with the tried and true root/blast strategy, which can work quite well if the root holds, but if you have your pet on them , they will need to root both of you, which a) takes time and b) usually allows you to get your key spells off (darkness/fear or darkness/DOTs). However, I bore witness to a duel wherein a wizard used shadow step extremely well to root both SK and pet and then used bolt spells outside of the SK spell range and crushed him without getting touched. Now, this wizard was extremely lucky in his SS warping and in the fact that none of his spells were resisted, but it goes to show you not to take wizard duels lightly.<P><P>Tanks: Ah, tanks. Tanks are designed to be melee fighters and hence will generally be able to take us in straight up melee, but this is where we temporarily become predominantly casters. Tanks, being melee machines, will ALWAYS yearn to be toe to toe with you, hence you simply need to deny them that luxury. A simple shadow step out of melee to give us casting time for darkness/fear/dot can make tank battles fairly swift and easy. Of course, when the fear breaks, the tank will come charging at you, at which point you can choose to remind you that you aren’t a weak little caster that can’t take/deliver melee damage, or you can play it safe and SS and repeat. Here HT can serve as a psychological advantage as well. If a warrior gets a critical hit on you for twice his normal damage and starts to think that he’s a badass, HT him to bring him back to earth. It usually serves to not only to cut their celebration short, but it also mocks them and gives them immediate cause for worry (varies depending on how much HP they have left). Plus, don’t forget the benefit of Siphon Strength, not only will it make them hit less, but many tanks are at close to their max encumbrance, hence a siphon strength will put them over and drop their agility as well.<P><P>General strategies to be aware of:<P>Harm Touch: in most situations, you want to save this for the killing blow (as mentioned above), but sometimes the psychological benefit can turn the tide of a battle (as mentioned in the tank strategy). A wizard that has just blasted away half your life will be scared stiff when your root breaks and you come charging up and take off half of his life in one attack. Most people will know that you can only use HT once, but the mere drop in HP is usually cause for panic.<P>Reaver of the Dead: It is always helpful to have one of these on hand due to the charge of Complete Heal. The Thex Mallet quest is relatively easy to do by yourself at 25+ and a small group of high teens low 20s shouldn’t have a problem in lower befallen. Always have the Reaver out in your inventory bound to a button, then, should the tide in battle turn against your favor, merely TAB to target yourself (VERY important) then right click on the button and you’ve got your very own LoH (Paladins HATE to see that).<P><P>Now, I know I didn’t mention hybrid strategies, but I felt it was best to merely present the ones above and allow you all to experiment with them and concoct some of your own for those (just keep in mind whether the hybrid is primarily tank or caster). Should you come across me on Druzzil (not Fennin) Ro, feel free to offer your thoughts on my advice. I wish you all the best of luck in your battles with the children of light.<P>-Zekris Shadowblaze<P> Dark Lord of the Divine Order of Chaos<P> ”May the shadows never succumb to the light…”</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
